                <h2>Why Do Recharge Amounts Often Not Match Platform Records?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Check for fees first, then investigate exchange rate factors.</strong></p>
<p>Most ad platforms don't charge extra fees for recharges, but third-party payment channels or agents may apply service charges. Keep payment receipts and compare the amount paid with the amount credited to the account. If using credit cards or third-party payment tools, the exchange rate is usually slightly higher than the bank's spot rate—this is normal and should be recorded for reconciliation.</p>
<h2>How to Handle Exchange Rate Differences in Multi-Platform Reconciliation?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Fix a settlement currency, record real-time rates, and convert monthly.</strong></p>
<p>When operating across Google, Meta, and TikTok simultaneously, settle all accounts in a single currency (CNY or USD). Record the real-time exchange rate at each recharge and convert monthly totals accordingly. Large fluctuations between the beginning and end of the month may create exchange gains or losses—record these separately in financial reports.</p>
<h2>What to Do When Invoice Amounts Don't Match Monthly Spend Reports?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Confirm the billing cycle, wait if delayed, and submit a dispute for large gaps.</strong></p>
<p>Ad platform invoices are typically issued in the first few working days of the following month. Minor differences (within 1%) may be due to timezone divisions—platforms often bill in UTC while your reports may use local time. Differences exceeding 5% warrant a formal dispute with the platform or your agency, with supporting screenshots.</p>
<h2>How to Efficiently Manage Financial Flows Across Multiple Ad Accounts?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Build separate ledgers by platform and account, set balance alerts, and reconcile regularly.</strong></p>
<p>For teams managing more than five accounts, manual tracking is error-prone. Create a dedicated ledger for each platform and account, recording recharge time, amount, exchange rate, and account ID. Conduct weekly balance checks and trigger recharge alerts when balance falls below three days of average daily spend.</p>
<h2>Who to Contact When Recharged Funds Remain Unspent or Show Abnormal Spend?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Verify account status and campaign settings first, then escalate to the platform or agency.</strong></p>
<p>Unspent balances usually indicate account suspension, misconfigured budgets, or targeting issues. Check platform dashboards to rule out operational errors, then submit a spend investigation request with recharge details and account ID. Expect a 3-7 business day response.</p>
<h2>How to Avoid Year-End Reconciliation Chaos?</h2>
<p><strong>Answer: Daily reconciliation habits are far more efficient than monthly fire drills.</strong></p>
<p>Fix weekly reconciliation sessions to export recharge records and spend reports. Verify each recharge upon arrival, maintain closed-loop records linking recharge-spend-invoice, and establish traceable documentation. Financial compliance isn't about perfection in one go—it's about stable, repeatable processes.</p>
